{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17570022","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17570022"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T00:36:23+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T00:36:23+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22638"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"22638","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/22638"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.41,0.15,0.32,0.08]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"15585"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112287"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"15585","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/15585"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22638"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94336"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"21"},{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1139"},{"type":"tags","id":"3455"},{"type":"tags","id":"9063"},{"type":"tags","id":"12921"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"45101"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45102"},{"type":"contributions","id":"46034"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112287","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/112287"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn 82-year-old man presents to hospital for investigation of dysphagia and weight loss over the past three months. He has a medical history of hypertension, hyperlipidaemia, and a 40 pack-year smoking history. His medications include amlodipine and atorvastatin. He is a retired plumber.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears cachectic with vital signs within normal limits. Abdominal examination is unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EEndoscopy reveals an adenocarcinoma of the oesophagus. A staging CT scan is performed and apart from the bulky tumour seen encasing the oesophagus, another finding is noted (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes this finding?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Pelvic kidney","Calcified mesenteric lymph nodes","Hepatic metastatic deposits","Iliac artery aneurysm","Carcinoma of the ascending colon"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe CT scan shows extensive calcification of the aorta and iliac vessels, with aneurysm formation in the left common iliac artery. This is an incidental finding and unrelated to the oesophageal adenocarcinoma. Incidental radiographic findings are relatively common, occurring in 30-40% of patients who have abdominal CT scans performed in emergency departments. These vary from simple findings like renal and hepatic cysts, which require no further investigation, to adrenal masses which need follow-up.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIliac artery aneurysm\u003C/strong\u003E is the correct answer. The image demonstrates focal dilatation of the left common iliac artery with extensive vascular calcification, characteristic of an aneurysm. Given the patient\u0027s age and primary diagnosis of oesophageal cancer, this incidental finding is unlikely to require immediate intervention.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPelvic kidney\u003C/strong\u003E would appear as renal tissue located in the pelvis rather than the normal retroperitoneal position. This congenital anomaly would show characteristic renal parenchyma with cortex and medulla, which is not present in this image.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECalcified mesenteric lymph nodes\u003C/strong\u003E typically appear as discrete, rounded overall calcifications within the mesentery, often resulting from previous granulomatous infection. The peripheral calcification pattern in this image follows vascular structures rather than lymph node distribution.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHepatic metastatic deposits\u003C/strong\u003E would appear as focal lesions within the liver parenchyma, often with different attenuation compared to normal liver tissue. The finding in this image is clearly extrahepatic and vascular in nature.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECarcinoma of the ascending colon\u003C/strong\u003E would present as bowel wall thickening or a mass arising from the colon. The structure shown is clearly vascular with calcification, not bowel-related.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Incidental findings on CT imaging are common, occurring in 30-40% of abdominal scans performed in emergency departments.","Iliac artery aneurysms appear as focal dilatations of the vessel with or without calcification on CT imaging.","Management of incidental vascular findings depends on size, patient factors, and the primary clinical condition."],"references":["O\u0027Sullivan JW, Muntinga T, Grigg S, et al. Prevalence and outcomes of incidental imaging findings: umbrella review. BMJ 2018;361. Available from: https://www.bmj.com/content/361/bmj.k2387","Bashir O, Sharma R, Bell D, et al. Iliac artery aneurysm. Reference article, Radiopaedia.org (Accessed on 06 Aug 2025) https://doi.org/10.53347/rID-17187"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94336"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22638"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"22014"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"22014","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/22014"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/XXUbBfEZFnDR7L9epsuDKO3YIrotdy